On Wed, 10 Jan 2007, Robt Mann wrote:

> the question remains where to put the k-thermocouple(s).
  	The std answer for aero engines is, substituting for spark-plug
  washer(s).  It is pretty clear  however from comments & pix by those who've
  done it on T2 engines that this is difficult to reconcile with ordinary
  removals & replacements of spark plugs.

  	If other places on the cyl head(s) are to be used for the
  thermocouple(s), it is then pointed out that the figures showing on the
  gauge(s) will differ significantly from those that would have been read from
  that position clamped to the head under a spark plug. But then, it has been 
> insisted all along that what matters with these figures is their trends, not 
> their absolute values.
> 	A thermocouple (or other T-sensor) in firm contact with a cyl head 
> will read something near the actual T of that cyl head, if covered with a 
> suitable thermal insulator.  A trap one can see in this idea is that passage 
> of cooling air past that part of the head might be impeded by this stuck-on 
> rig, which could cause serious trouble.
>
> R
